I have successfully implemented the comprehensive test infrastructure for the OpenPrint Cloud project. Here's a summary of what was created:

## Test Utilities Package (`internal/testutil/`)

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `db.go` (existing) | PostgreSQL testcontainer setup |
| `migrate.go` (existing) | Database migration helpers |
| `fixtures.go` (existing) | Test data fixtures |
| **`redis.go`** | Redis testcontainer setup with pub/sub, cluster, and module support |
| **`s3.go`** | MinIO/S3 testcontainer setup with bucket/object operations |
| **`jwt.go`** | JWT token generation helpers with fluent builder API |
| **`http.go`** | HTTP test server wrapper with request recording |
| **`context.go`** | Test context management with timeouts/cancellation |
| **`config.go`** | Test configuration with isolated environment variables |
| **`assertions.go`** | Custom assertion helpers for cleaner test code |
| **`metrics.go`** | Test metrics collection and reporting |

## Scripts & Build Files

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| **`scripts/test-env.sh`** | Bootstrap script for Docker/dependency checks |
| **`Makefile`** | Comprehensive test targets (unit, integration, coverage, race, benchmarks) |
| **`.github/workflows/test.yml`** | CI/CD pipeline with parallel test jobs |

## Database Migrations (Market-Driven Features)

| Migration | Features |
|-----------|----------|
| `000022_create_print_quotas` | Print quotas, cost tracking, usage limits |
| `000023_create_print_policies` | Print policy engine with rules and evaluations |
| `000024_create_secure_release` | Secure print release with PIN/card/NFC |
| `000025_create_mfa` | MFA support (TOTP, SMS, smart cards, hardware tokens) |
| `000026_create_analytics` | Daily/weekly/monthly usage aggregation and reporting |

## Makefile Targets

```bash
make test              # Run all tests
make test-unit         # Unit tests only
make test-integration  # Integration tests (requires Docker)
make test-cover        # Generate coverage report
make test-bench        # Run benchmarks
make test-env          # Check test environment
```
